# Personal Expense Tracker CLI — project rules

These rules pin the project's engineering constraints so generated code stays in-scope and the diff
surface stays small. They make context-scoping reproducible (a standing rule) rather than relying only
on manual `@`-mentions per prompt.

## Runtime & dependencies
- Standard library only at **runtime**. Do not add third-party runtime dependencies to `pyproject.toml`.
- `pytest`, `mypy`, and `ruff` are dev-only dependencies.
- Target Python ≥ 3.11. Use `from __future__ import annotations` at the top of every module.

## Money & dates
- Represent money with `decimal.Decimal`, never `float`. Serialize amounts as **strings** in JSON.
- Render money with exactly two decimal places (`f"{value:.2f}"`).
- Dates are `datetime.date`, serialized as ISO `YYYY-MM-DD`. Months are `YYYY-MM` strings.

## CLI & errors
- One `argparse` parser with `add` / `list` / `summary` subcommands; entry point is
  `expense_tracker.__main__:main` returning an `int` exit code.
- Validate user input before persisting. Invalid input prints a clear message to **stderr**, returns a
  non-zero exit code, and writes nothing.
- Wrap only system boundaries (user input, file I/O) in `try/except`. Surface store problems as
  `StoreError`. No defensive `try/except` around internal calls.

## Quality gates (must stay green)
- `mypy --strict` clean — full type hints, no `# type: ignore`.
- `ruff check` clean (E, F, I, B, UP, RUF) — no `# noqa` unless justified inline.
- Every acceptance criterion has a behavior-focused test; tests use `tmp_path`, not real user files.
- No TODO/FIXME comments and no teaching comments in delivered code.
